{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638995"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:01:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:01:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17753"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17753"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75826"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10467"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17753"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61339"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1164"},{"type":"tags","id":"4625"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7102"},{"type":"tags","id":"8851"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24434"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24435"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75826","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75826"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 69-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with his wife, who reports that he developed slurred speech and facial asymmetry since yesterday, more than 24 hours ago. He has a longstanding history of hypertension and a past medical history of myocardial infarction and pulmonary embolism. He does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits, but his speech is slurred, and there is noticeable facial droop on the right side.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medical emergencies is the patient most likely experiencing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stroke","Transient ischaemic attack","Bell\u0027s palsy","Hypoglycaemia","Seizure"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sudden onset of \u003Cstrong\u003Eslurred speech\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Efacial asymmetry\u003C/strong\u003E in this patient, especially given his history of hypertension, is highly suggestive of a \u003Cstrong\u003Estroke\u003C/strong\u003E. Strokes can be ischaemic or haemorrhagic, and immediate medical evaluation is necessary to determine the appropriate management, which may include thrombolysis if appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etransient ischaemic attack\u003C/strong\u003E could present similarly but resolves within minutes to hours without permanent deficits. The persistent nature of this patient\u0027s symptoms makes a stroke more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBell\u0027s palsy\u003C/strong\u003E causes facial asymmetry but not slurred speech unless there is significant facial muscle involvement. Bell\u0027s palsy usually presents with isolated facial nerve palsy without other neurological deficits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypoglycaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can cause neurological symptoms, including slurred speech, but would be accompanied by other symptoms such as confusion, sweating, or altered consciousness. The facial asymmetry is less characteristic of hypoglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eseizure\u003C/strong\u003E could cause transient neurological symptoms, but the presentation of slurred speech and facial droop without other seizure activity makes this less likely. Postictal states can cause temporary neurological deficits, but the history and examination findings are more consistent with a stroke.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A sudden onset of slurred speech and facial asymmetry in an elderly patient with a history of hypertension suggests a stroke.","Immediate recognition and management of stroke symptoms are crucial to improve outcomes.","Hypertension is a significant risk factor for stroke."],"references":["Boehme AK, Esenwa C, Elkind MS. Stroke Risk Factors, Genetics, and Prevention. Circ Res. 2017 Feb 3;120(3):472-495. doi: 10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.116.308398. PMID: 28154098; PMCID: PMC5321635.","Boehme AK, Esenwa C, Elkind MS. Stroke Risk Factors, Genetics, and Prevention. Circ Res. 2017 Feb 3;120(3):472-495. doi: 10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.116.308398. PMID: 28154098; PMCID: PMC5321635.","Yew KS, Cheng E. Acute stroke diagnosis. Am Fam Physician. 2009 Jul 1;80(1):33-40. PMID: 19621844; PMCID: PMC2722757.","Hurford R, Sekhar A, Hughes TAT, Muir KW. Diagnosis and management of acute ischaemic stroke. Pract Neurol. 2020 Aug;20(4):304-316. doi: 10.1136/practneurol-2020-002557. Epub 2020 Jun 7. PMID: 32507747; PMCID: PMC7577107."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61339"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17753"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61339","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61339"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-31T20:59:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-31T20:59:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10467"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75826"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"